('dac8fa63-efdd-4db9-b809-59bfb24b8bb6', 1, '2024-06-25 05:17:43', '<p>A 54-year-old woman presents to A and E with severe abdominal pain, diarrhoea and vomiting for the past two days. She reports her symptoms started after she ate sushi at a local restaurant. Her past medical history includes diabetes.</p>\n<p>On physical examination, the patient appears dehydrated with dry mucous membranes and decreased skin turgor. Abdominal examination reveals diffuse tenderness. Her extremities are cold.</p>\n<p>Her blood pressure is 95/60 mmHg, heart rate is 110 bpm and respiratory rate is 23/min.</p>\n<p>Her blood results are as follows:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Creatinine: 300 μmol/L</li>\n<li>K+: 5.0 mmol/L</li>\n<li>Na+: 132 mmol/L</li>\n<li>Urinalysis: Muddy brown casts</li>\n<li>Urine osmolarity: 300 mOsm/kg</li>\n</ul>\n', 'Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?', 3, '\"[{\\\"text\\\":\\\"IgA nephropathy\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"IgA nephropathy presents with hematuria following an upper respiratory tract infection, not gastrointestinal symptoms like diarrhoea and vomiting.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Prerenal azotemia\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Prerenal azotemia is characterised by high urine osmolarity (> 500 mOsm\\\\/kg) which makes the diagnosis unlikely.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Acute tubular necrosis\\\",\\\"value\\\":true,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Acute tubular necrosis is a form of acute kidney injury resulting from intrinsic damage to renal tubules due to ischemia or exposure to nephrotoxic agents.<br>\\\\nIn this scenario, a 54-year-old woman presented with diarrhoea due to suspected food poisoning resulting in significant fluid loss from the GI tract and dehydration. Hypovolaemic states such as diarrhoea are known precipitants of acute tubular necrosis. Hypovolaemia results in reduced renal blood flow and subsequent ischemic injury.<br>\\\\nHer blood results such as elevated serum creatinine and hyperkalemia further support a diagnosis of acute tubular necrosis, as does the presence of muddy brown cast in her urine and a urine osmolarity of <320 mOsm\\\\/kg.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Acute interstitial nephritis\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Acute interstitial nephritis is caused due to drug hypersensitivity and presents with rash, fever and eosinophilia.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Glomerulonephritis\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Glomerulonephritis typically presents with haematuria, proteinuria and often systemic symptoms like oedema and hypertension. It is not usually associated with acute dehydration and muddy brown casts.\\\"}]\"', NULL, NULL, 'published', '2024-06-25 04:38:28', NULL, NULL, '2024-06-25 05:17:44', '2024-06-25 05:17:44', NULL),
('74ca3619-b709-4c58-b33b-b45633cf30fa', 1, '2024-06-25 05:21:31', '<p>A 25 year old woman presents to the clinic with a 3 week history of persistent cough, night sweats and unintentional weight loss. She has no significant past medical history but mentions she recently returned from a trip from central Africa.</p>\n<p>On examination, she has a low-grade fever and crackles in the right upper lobe of her lung. A chest X-ray reveals a small cavitary lesion in the right upper lobe.</p>\n', 'Which of the following is the most appropriate next step in the management of this patient?', 4, '\"[{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Broad spectrum antibiotics\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"This approach is inappropriate without confirming the diagnosis. While antibiotics are part of the treatment for bacterial infections, the clinical presentation and epidemiological background strongly suggest tuberculosis (TB), for which specific antimycobacterial therapy is required.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Acid-fast bacillus smear and culture\\\",\\\"value\\\":true,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Given the symptoms, radiological findings and recent travel history to a high TB-prevalence area, it is crucial to confirm the diagnosis of TB. A sputum smear and culture for acid-fast bacilli are essential to identify Mycobacterium tuberculosis and guide specific treatment.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Oral corticosteroids\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"This could potentially worsen the patient\'s condition by suppressing the immune response, especially if the patient has active TB, without confirming the diagnosis and starting appropriate anti-TB treatment.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Lung lobectomy\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"This is an overly aggressive approach for a suspected case of TB without confirmed diagnosis and attempt at medical management. Surgery is reserved for specific complications or resistance scenarios in TB management.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Bed rest and increased fluid intake\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"While supportive care is important, it does not address the underlying cause. This patient needs specific diagnostic and therapeutic interventions for TB, not just symptomatic relief.\\\"}]\"', NULL, NULL, 'published', '2024-06-25 04:38:28', NULL, NULL, '2024-06-25 05:21:31', '2024-06-25 05:21:31', NULL),
('efc79d20-1e14-4516-b27d-1f5d3291810a', 1, '2024-06-25 05:24:26', '<p>A 22 year old female university student presents to the Emergency Department with a severe headache, photophobia, neck stiffness and a high fever.</p>\n<p>On examination, there is a positive Brudzinski sign and a petechial rash on her lower extremities. Her vital signs include a temperature of 39.5°C, heart rate of 110 bpm, blood pressure of 90/60 mmHg and a respiratory rate of 22 breaths per minute. She appears drowsy but responds to verbal stimuli.</p>\n<p>A lumbar puncture is performed, and the cerebrospinal fluid (CSF) shows an increased white cell count predominantly of neutrophils, elevated protein and low glucose levels.</p>\n', 'What is the most likely causative organism?', 1, '\"[{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Neisseria meningitidis\\\",\\\"value\\\":true,\\\"note\\\":\\\"This is the most likely causative organism for several reasons. The patient\'s symptoms of severe headache, photophobia, neck stiffness, high fever and the presence of a petechial rash are highly indicative of meningococcal meningitis. Neisseria meningitidis is a common cause of bacterial meningitis in young adults and can lead to rapidly progressive sepsis, which is consistent with her vital signs indicating septic shock.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Streptococcus pneumoniae\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"While Streptococcus pneumoniae is a common cause of bacterial meningitis, especially in children and older adults, it is less associated with a petechial rash. The clinical presentation here strongly points towards Neisseria meningitidis rather than pneumococcal meningitis.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Haemophilus influenzae type b\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"This organism used to be a common cause of bacterial meningitis in children, however the incidence has significantly decreased due to widespread vaccination. It is less common in adults and does not typically present with a petechial rash.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Listeria monocytogenes\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Listeria monocytogenes can cause meningitis, especially in neonates, elderly patients and immunocompromised individuals. It is less common in young, otherwise healthy adults and does not typically present with a petechial rash.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Mycobacterium tuberculosis\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Tuberculous meningitis usually presents more insidiously with symptoms developing over weeks to months. It is characterised by a lymphocytic rather than a neutrophilic predominance in the CSF, and the CSF glucose levels are typically very low. A petechial rash is not associated with TB meningitis.\\\"}]\"', NULL, NULL, 'published', '2024-06-25 04:38:28', NULL, NULL, '2024-06-25 05:24:27', '2024-06-25 05:24:27', NULL),
('60b347bb-9132-4323-951d-2f1d7d7854c4', 1, '2024-06-25 05:28:34', '<p>A 60 year old woman presents to the GP with progressive fatigue, jaundice and dark urine for the past week. She has a history of sickle cell trait, hypertension and type 2 diabetes mellitus.</p>\n<p>She has no history of recent travel, new medications or significant changes in her diet. On examination, she is icteric with mild tenderness in the RUQ and a palpable spleen 2cm below the costal margin. Her observations are stable.</p>\n<p>Blood tests reveal the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Haemoglobin: 90 g/L (120-160 g/L)</li>\n<li>Reticulocyte count: 5% (0.5-2.5%)</li>\n<li>Total bilirubin: 68 µmol/L (3-17 µmol/L)</li>\n<li>AST: 45 U/L (10-40 U/L)</li>\n<li>ALT: 50 U/L (7-56 U/L)</li>\n<li>LDH: 600 U/L (135-225 U/L)</li>\n<li>Haptoglobin: undetectable</li>\n<li>G6PD level: normal</li>\n</ul>\n', 'What is the most likely diagnosis?', 9, '\"[{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Sickle cell crisis\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Sickle cell crisis is typically associated with sickle cell disease rather than sickle cell trait. Sickle cell crisis usually presents with severe pain due to vaso-occlusion, which is not mentioned in this patient\'s symptoms. The presentation of jaundice and dark urine, along with the specific lab findings, is more consistent with haemolysis rather than a sickle cell crisis in someone with only the trait.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Autoimmune haemolytic anaemia\\\",\\\"value\\\":true,\\\"note\\\":\\\"The patient\'s signs of haemolysis (jaundice, dark urine, elevated total and direct bilirubin, high reticulocyte count, significantly elevated LDH and undetectable haptoglobin) indicate a haemolytic process. The normal G6PD levels rule out G6PD deficiency as a cause. Autoimmune haemolytic anaemia is a condition where the body\'s immune system destroys red blood cells, leading to the observed symptoms and laboratory findings.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Wilson\\\\u2019s Disease\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Wilson\\\\u2019s disease is a genetic disorder that causes copper accumulation in tissues, leading to hepatic and neurological symptoms. While it can cause liver dysfunction and jaundice, it typically presents earlier in life and is associated with specific neurological symptoms, Kayser-Fleischer rings in the eyes and more marked liver enzyme abnormalities.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Gilbert\'s syndrome\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Gilbert\'s syndrome causes mild, unconjugated hyperbilirubinaemia and typically does not cause significant jaundice or other signs of haemolysis such as elevated reticulocyte count or undetectable haptoglobin. The degree of jaundice and haemolytic markers observed in this patient is too severe for Gilbert\'s syndrome.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Hereditary spherocytosis\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Hereditary spherocytosis can present with haemolytic anaemia, jaundice and splenomegaly. However, it is usually diagnosed earlier in life and is less likely to present for the first time in a 60-year-old. Moreover, the patient\'s clinical history and lab findings align more closely with autoimmune haemolytic anaemia.\\\"}]\"', NULL, NULL, 'published', '2024-06-25 04:38:28', NULL, NULL, '2024-06-25 05:28:34', '2024-06-25 05:28:34', NULL),
('c6e671ea-881a-4602-816b-05dcfb4152ef', 1, '2024-06-25 05:31:09', '<p>32 year old man presents to his GP with well-demarcated, erythematous plaques covered with silvery scales on his elbows and knees. He also complains of occasional joint pain, particularly in his fingers. The plaques have been present for the past 6 months and have progressively worsened despite over the counter emollients. He mentions that his father had a similar condition.</p>\n<p>On examination, the plaques are noted to be 2-5 cm in diameter, with a positive Auspitz sign. His BMI is 28 and he reports a recent increase in weight. He has no significant past medical history otherwise and is not currently on any medication.</p>', 'What is the most appropriate initial treatment?', 20, '\"[{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Topical corticosteroids\\\",\\\"value\\\":true,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Topical corticosteroids are the first line treatment for mild to moderate psoriasis. They reduce inflammation and slow the turnover of skin cells which helps to clear plaques. Given his presentation with localised plaques this is the most appropriate initial treatment.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Methotrexate\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Methotrexate is a systemic treatment used for more severe cases of psoriasis or psoriatic arthritis. It is not typically initiated as the first line of treatment for mild to moderate skin symptoms. It would be considered if topical treatments and other measures fail or if the disease is more widespread or significantly impacting the patient\\\\u2019s quality of life.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Phototherapy\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Phototherapy, or light therapy, is another option for moderate to severe psoriasis but is generally not the initial treatment choice unless topical treatments fail or are unsuitable. It might be considered in cases where the disease is extensive or not adequately controlled with topical treatments.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Topical calcineurin inhibitors\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"These are used mainly for sensitive skin areas, such as the face and flexures, but are not first-line treatments for typical plaque psoriasis on elbows and knees. They are useful in areas where corticosteroids are less desirable due to potential side effects.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Oral corticosteroids\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Oral corticosteroids are generally not recommended for psoriasis because they can cause a rebound effect which can lead to a flare-up of the disease once the medication is stopped. This approach is therefore not suitable for initial management of psoriasis.\\\"}]\"', NULL, NULL, 'published', '2024-06-25 04:38:28', NULL, NULL, '2024-06-25 05:31:09', '2024-06-25 05:31:09', NULL),
('0ee9a5df-f808-440d-ae74-bee58c3342cc', 1, '2024-06-25 05:35:32', '<p>A 45 year old woman presents to clinic with a 6 month history of progressive muscle weakness and a rash. She reports difficulty climbing stairs and rising from a seated position. On examination, she has a violet-coloured rash over her eyelids and erythematous papules over her knuckles.</p>\n<p>Laboratory tests reveal the following:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Creatine kinase (CK): 1250 U/L (normal: 38-174 U/L)</li>\n<li>ESR: 50 mm/hr (normal <20)</li>\n<li>ANA: Positive</li>\n<li>Anti-Jo-1 antibody: Positive</li>\n</ul>\n', 'What is the most likely diagnosis?', 22, '\"[{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Systemic lupus erythematosus\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"While systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) can present with a variety of systemic symptoms and a positive ANA, it typically does not present with the specific muscle weakness and characteristic skin findings seen in this patient (heliotrope rash and Gottron\\\\u2019s papules). Elevated CK is also more indicative of muscle inflammation rather than SLE.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Polymyalgia rheumatica\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Polymyalgia rheumatica typically presents with pain and stiffness in the shoulders and hips, not muscle weakness. It is also more common in patients over the age of 50 and is not associated with elevated CK or specific rashes like heliotrope rash and Gottron\\\\u2019s papules.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Dermatomyositis\\\",\\\"value\\\":true,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Dermatomyositis is characterised by progressive muscle weakness, often involving the proximal muscles, and distinctive skin manifestations such as a heliotrope rash and Gottron\\\\u2019s papules. The elevated CK indicates muscle inflammation, and the presence of anti-Jo-1 antibodies is consistent with this diagnosis.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Rheumatoid arthritis\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Rheumatoid arthritis typically presents with symmetrical joint inflammation and does not usually cause muscle weakness or the characteristic rashes described. Elevated CK and the specific skin findings are not typical for rheumatoid arthritis.\\\"},{\\\"text\\\":\\\"Systemic sclerosis\\\",\\\"value\\\":null,\\\"note\\\":\\\"Systemic sclerosis can present with skin changes and positive ANA, but it is more commonly associated with skin tightening and fibrosis rather than muscle weakness and the specific rashes seen in dermatomyositis. Elevated CK is also not typical of systemic sclerosis.\\\"}]\"', NULL, NULL, 'published', '2024-06-25 04:38:28', NULL, NULL, '2024-06-25 05:35:32', '2024-06-25 05:35:32', NULL);